I can’t stop thinking about these crazy $AAPL price increases.

We’ve never seen anything like this in consumer electronics, ever. It’s not new products, just current or even very old products. 

On top of it, iPhone 18 looking at a $200+ bump.

How this will play out for demand? https://t.co/6jKZ5qUgbU

Whatever happens, somebody will probably become a professor in microeconomics studying this. 

It’s an incredible experiment in price, supply and demand for discretionary goods on a global scale that we’ve never seen before.

@thc_btc Funnily enough, they did not raise trade-in prices! But they did raise prices and refurbished by the same amounts!

@ReneSellmann I genuinely have never seen anything even close to this. This is a historic move, most people who don’t know microeconomics well cannot fathom the sheer scale of this.

Funnily enough, my bull case for Apple revenue growth was price increases… and oh boy did we get them.

@guillesla That’s what we will find out.

@KairockZ That’s for sure.

@MomAngtrades If sales volumes go down, they will likely add some forced obsolescence. This year they did the opposite, with iOS 27 being much much faster and better on older devices vs iOS 26, but things may change if volume takes a nosedive.

@seajlim The HomePod mini is from 2019… and they bumped it 30%! And it only has 1GB of RAM anyway.

